  "prompt": "Is the activity of money laundering prohibited?",
  "response": "Yes, the activity of **money laundering** is **prohibited** and is considered a **criminal offense** in virtually all jurisdictions worldwide. Money laundering involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained funds to make them appear legitimate. This process typically involves three stages: **placement** (introducing illicit funds into the financial system), **layering** (concealing the source through complex transactions), and **integration** (reintroducing the \"cleaned\" money into the economy as legitimate funds).\n\nGovernments and international organizations have established stringent laws and regulations to combat money laundering, as it facilitates organized crime, terrorism, corruption, and other illegal activities. Key international frameworks include:\n\n1. **The Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**: A global watchdog that sets standards and promotes policies to combat money laundering and terrorist financing.\n2. **National Legislation**: Most countries have their own anti-money laundering (AML) laws, which often require financial institutions to implement measures such as customer due diligence, reporting suspicious activities, and record-keeping.\n\nPenalties for money laundering can be severe, including **fines**, **imprisonment**, and **asset forfeiture**. Additionally, businesses found complicit in money laundering may face reputational damage, loss of licenses, and other sanctions.",
